docs.abstract: A crew contracted by Columbia Gas mishandled high-pressure gas as it replaced old pipes, according to a preliminary report by the National Transportation Safety Board.
docs.snippet: A crew contracted by Columbia Gas mishandled high-pressure gas as it replaced old pipes, according to a preliminary report by the National Transportation Safety Board.
docs.lead_paragraph: A faulty plan to replace aging gas pipes caused sudden explosions and fires in three towns north of Boston last month that killed one person and drove thousands from their homes, the National Transportation Safety Board said Thursday.

headline.main: Faulty Work by Gas Company Caused Massachusetts Explosions, Officials Say
headline.print_headline: Faulty Work Caused Blasts Near Boston, Officials Say

docs.abstract: Columbia Gas has agreed to sell its business in the state and pay a $53 million fine, the authorities said.
docs.snippet: Columbia Gas has agreed to sell its business in the state and pay a $53 million fine, the authorities said.
docs.lead_paragraph: Almost 18 months after a series of explosions in northeastern Massachusetts in 2018, a gas company has agreed to plead guilty to violating federal pipeline safety laws, pay a $53 million fine and sell its business in the state, the authorities said Wednesday.

headline.main: Massachusetts Gas Company to Plead Guilty After Fatal Explosion
headline.print_headline: Gas Company to Plead Guilty Over Fires

byline.original: By Mihir Zaveri and Jacey Fortin
